'''Ailbhe Mac Shamhráin''' (31 August 1954 – 29 June 2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://notices.irishtimes.com/10400720 |title=MacSHAMHRÁIN, Ailbhe : Death notice - Irish Times Family Notices - Irish Times |publisher=Notices.irishtimes.com |date=2011-07-24 |accessdate=2011-11-18}}</ref> was an Irish [[medieval historian]] and [[Celtic Studies|celticist]].
==Career== Mac Shamhráin studied at [[University College Dublin]] and [[Trinity College Dublin]]. He was then a [[research associate]] at Scoil an Léinn Cheiltigh, [[Maynooth University|NUI Maynooth]]. Previously, he taught early [[Irish history]] & settlement studies at Trinity, [[St. Patrick's College, Drumcondra|St. Patrick's College Drumcondra]], and NUI Maynooth, where he lectured on the Medieval Irish Studies Programme at the Department of [[Old Irish|Old]] and [[Middle Irish]]. Prior to that, he taught History and [[Irish language|Irish]] at [[Belcamp College]] Secondary School.<ref>A MacShamhrain (ed), The Island of St. Patrick (Dublin, 2004), p. 180 (notes on contributors).</ref>
In recent years, Mac Shamhráin has led and managed the Monasticon Hibernicum Project (funded by the [[Irish Research Council]] for the [[Humanities]] and [[Social Sciences]]). His [[database]] of [[Early Christianity|Early Christian]] [[Ecclesiastical]] Settlement in [[Ireland]] from the 5th to the 12th centuries was published [[online]] in 2009. He has also published a number of papers on early [[Irish politics|Irish political]] and [[ecclesiastical history]], and has contributed over 300 entries to the [[Dictionary of Irish Biography]].<ref>A MacShamhrain, Lives of the Irish Saints: A brief Introduction (Dublin, 2009), p.4 (note on the author).</ref> Mac Shamhráin died in Dublin on 29 June 2011, after a long illness. He continued to write throughout, and completed his final article in hospital on the day of his death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://notices.irishtimes.com/10400720 |title=MacSHAMHRÁIN, Ailbhe : Death notice - Irish Times Family Notices - Irish Times |publisher=Notices.irishtimes.com |date=2011-07-24 |accessdate=2011-11-18}}</ref>
==Select bibliography== * ''Prosopographica Glindelachensis: the [[monasticism|Monastic]] Church of [[Glendalough]] and its Community, Sixth to Thirteenth Centuries,'' in ''[[Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland]]'', No. 119, pp.&nbsp;82–84. 1989. * ''The Uí Muiredaig and the [[Abbey]] of Glendalough in the Eleventh to Thirteenth Centuries,'' in ''Cambrian Medieval Celtic Studies,'' No. 25, pp.&nbsp;55–75. 1993. * ''Church and Polity in Pre-Norman Ireland,'' May 1996. * ''"Nebulae discutiuntur"? The Emergence of [[Clann Cholmáin]], Sixth - Eighth Centuries,'' pp.&nbsp;83–97, in Alfred P. Smyth (ed.), ''Seanchas: Studies in Early and Medieval Irish Archaeology, History and Literature in Honour of Francis J. Byrne''. Dublin: Four Courts, 2000. {{ISBN|978-1-85182-489-2}} * ''The [[Vikings]]: an Illustrated History,'' Dublin, 2002. * ''The Island of [[St. Patrick]]: Church and Ruling [[dynasty|Dynasties]] in Fingal and Meath, 400-1148,'' (ed.) Dublin: Four Courts, 2004 ** ''An Ecclesiastical Enclosure in the Townland of Grange, [[Parish (Catholic Church)|parish]] of Holmpatrick,'' ibid, pp.&nbsp;52–60 ** ''Church and Dynasty in Early Christian [[Brega]]: Lusk, Inis Pátraic and the Cast of Máel-Finnia, King and Saint,'' ibid, pp.&nbsp;125–39. * Database of Early Christian Ecclesiastical Settlement in Ireland 5th - 12th Centuries (with N. White & A. Breen) [[Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies|Dublin Institute of Advanced Studies]] (DIAS) 2009 [http://monasticon.celt.dias.ie]
