[[File:Roman Empire - Africa Proconsularis (125 AD).svg|thumb|right|[[Roman North Africa|Africa Proconsularis]] (125 AD).]]'''Aïn Tebernoc''' is a former [[Catholic]] [[diocese]] and [[archaeology|archaeological]] site in [[Tunisia]].

==History==
Aïn Tebernoc has numerous [[Roman Empire|Roman era]] [[ruins]] and is tentatively identified as the site of the ancient city of Tubernuca,<ref>Reinhart Herzog, Peter Lebrechtschmidt , [Handbook of the Latin Literature of Antiquity, Issue 5 ] (CHBeck , 1989).</ref> a [[municipum]] of the [[Roman Province]] of [[Roman North Africa|Africa Proconsolare]]<ref>[[Joseph-Anatole Toulotte]], Geography of Christian Africa: Proconsular.  Author:  (Rennes, 1892) [http://en.calameo.com/read/000107044db714fb368c9  p312].</ref>Numerous inscriptions in situ confirm the name and status of the Roman city.<ref>Joseph-Anatole Toulotte, Géographie de l'Afrique chrétienne(Rennes, 1892) [http://en.calameo.com/read/000107044db714fb368c9   p299].</ref>

Following the [[Reconquista]] of [[Spain]], a group of [[Andalusia]]n [[Moors]] settled in its [[ruins]] at the end of the [[15th century]]. 

Ancient Tubernuca was also the [[cathedra|seat]] of an ancient [[Catholic]] [[Bishopric]].<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/former/t1867.htmTitular Episcopal See of  Tubernuca] at GCatholic.org.</ref> It was a suffragan of [[Archdiocese of Carthage|Carthage]], which survives today as a [[titular Bishop]]ric of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. On one [[bishop]] from [[Ancient history|antiquity]] is known to us, Repositus, a correspondent with [[Cyprian]].<ref>[[Joseph-Anatole Toulotte]], Géographie de l'Afrique chrétienne(Rennes, 1892) [http://en.calameo.com/read/000107044db714fb368c9   p299].</ref> The current bishop of the [[Bishopric]] is [[Rubén Gonzalez Tierrablanca]] of [[Turkey]] who replaced [[Alberto Jiménez Iniesta]] of [[Spain]] in 2016.

